T1  - An analysis of value destruction in AT&T's acquisition of NCR
AU  - Lys, Thomas
AU  - Vincent, Linda
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 39
IS  - 2
SP  - 353
EP  - 378
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/10/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(95)00831-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X9500831X
KW  - Mergers
KW  - Acquisitions
KW  - Purchase
KW  - Pooling
AB  - AT&T's $7.5 billion acquisition of NCR decreased the wealth of AT&T shareholders by between $3.9 billion and $6.5 billion and resulted in negative synergies of $1.3 to $3.0 billion. We find that AT&T paid a documented $50 million and possibly as much as $500 million to satisfy pooling accounting, thus boosting EPS by roughly 17% but leaving cash flows unchanged. We conclude that AT&T's decision to acquire NCR in what the market perceived as a value-destroying transaction was related at least in part to the 1984 consent decree with the Department of Justice that led to the break-up of AT&T.
ER  - 

